{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500416"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:13:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:13:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1641"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1641"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.12,0.03,0.74,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91936"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1641"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75402"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"582"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1413"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31382"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39060"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91936"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of abdominal distension and vague abdominal discomfort. She lives in a rural town and rarely seeks medical attention. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She smokes 15 cigarettes daily and drinks five standard drinks daily, with increased consumption on weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears thin with a distended abdomen. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are dilated subcutaneous veins radiating from her umbilicus (Image). Several spider naevi are noted on her upper chest. The abdomen is non-tender with shifting dullness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inferior vena caval obstruction","Portal vein thrombosis","Hepatic vein occlusion","Cirrhosis","Superior vena cava obstruction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic signs of portal hypertension including caput medusae (dilated periumbilical veins), spider naevi and ascites. Given her significant alcohol intake, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. Portal hypertension in cirrhosis leads to the development of porto-systemic collaterals as blood seeks alternative pathways back to the systemic circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior vena caval obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with bilateral lower limb oedema and prominent superficial abdominal wall veins running in a caudal-cranial direction along the inferior and superior epigastric vessels. These patients often have significant haemodynamic compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPortal vein thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause similar signs of portal hypertension but is much less common than cirrhosis and would be unlikely to present so insidiously. It typically causes acute abdominal pain and requires immediate intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic vein occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E (Budd-Chiari syndrome) is a rare condition that typically occurs in patients with underlying prothrombotic conditions. While it can cause similar features, the acute presentation and absence of prothrombotic risk factors make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior vena cava obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically presents with facial and upper limb oedema, along with dilated chest wall veins. While this patient\u0027s smoking history puts her at risk of lung cancer (a common cause of SVC obstruction), her presentation is not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe history of chronic alcohol use, together with the clinical findings of spider naevi, ascites, and caput medusae, strongly supports alcoholic cirrhosis as the underlying diagnosis. Further workup would include liver function tests, coagulation studies, and ultrasound to confirm the diagnosis and assess for complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Caput medusae (dilated periumbilical veins) is a sign of portal hypertension, most commonly due to cirrhosis","Spider naevi (telangiectasia) on the upper body are a cutaneous marker of chronic liver disease","The combination of daily alcohol intake, ascites, and portal-systemic collaterals strongly suggests alcoholic cirrhosis"],"references":["Lawrensia S, Khan YS. Inferior vena cava syndrome. Statpearls [Internet]. 2020 December 13. Accessible from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560885/.","Bayraktar UD, Seren S, Bayraktar Y. Hepatic venous outflow obstruction: three similar syndromes. World J Gastroenterol. 2007; 13(13): 1912-27.","Nickson C. Superior Vena Cava (SVC) Obstruction [Internet]. Sydney (NSW): Life in the fast lane; 2020 [cited Feb 7 2021]. Available from: https://litfl.com/superior-vena-cava-svc-obstruction/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75402"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1641"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18354"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18354"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ca310192-1b10-462b-992c-5f19b6a0c465.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ca310192-1b10-462b-992c-5f19b6a0c465.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":525}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75402"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-16T15:14:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-16T12:54:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1641"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91936"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null